3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Hyperliquid calculates funding rates every hour based on the premium between perpetual and mark prices. The DEX uses a TWAP mechanism across the funding period, with payments occurring at the top of each hour. Unlike traditional CEXs, all calculations happen on-chain with sub-second finality, providing transparent rate discovery. Funding payments are automatically settled through the protocol's native USDC collateral system."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","SUI","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SUI's status as a Layer 1 blockchain with significant ecosystem development creates funding rate volatility ideal for arbitrage. The token's correlation with broader L1 narratives and DeFi activity generates periods of sustained positive or negative funding rates. Hyperliquid's hourly intervals provide more frequent arbitrage opportunities compared to traditional 8-hour cycles."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"SUI Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SUI funding rates on Hyperliquid typically range from -0.1% to 0.3% per hour during normal market conditions. During ecosystem announcements or major DeFi launches on Sui, rates can spike above 0.5% as retail traders pile into long positions. Negative rates often occur during broader market downturns or when SUI underperforms other L1 tokens. The hourly reset mechanism means arbitrageurs can capture these moves more frequently than on traditional exchanges. Historical data shows SUI maintains funding rate premiums during network upgrade cycles and major partnership announcements."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Strategy"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Hyperliquid's 1-hour funding intervals create 24 daily opportunities versus 3 on most CEXs, significantly increasing potential returns. Optimal strategies involve monitoring SUI ecosystem developments and positioning before announcement-driven volatility. Cross-exchange arbitrage works well by taking opposite positions on Hyperliquid versus Binance or OKX during rate divergences. The DEX's instant settlement and no KYC requirements enable rapid position adjustments. Automated strategies can exploit the predictable hourly timing and Hyperliquid's API for systematic funding collection."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Hyperliquid's single-chain architecture concentrates smart contract risk, requiring position sizing adjustments compared to established CEXs. USDC-only collateral means exposure to stablecoin depeg risks that don't exist with multi-collateral exchanges. The DEX's newer operational history provides less data on extreme market stress testing. Funding rate volatility on SUI can exceed expectations during L1 narrative shifts, requiring wider stop-losses. Liquidity during major moves may be lower than tier-1 CEXs, impacting large position exits."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How do SUI funding rates on Hyperliquid compare to centralized exchanges?","answer":"Hyperliquid's hourly funding intervals create more frequent rate adjustments, often resulting in higher absolute rates than CEXs with 8-hour cycles. The on-chain mechanism typically produces less manipulation and more transparent price discovery than traditional platforms."},{"question":"What makes SUI particularly suitable for funding rate arbitrage?","answer":"SUI's volatility as an emerging L1 token creates significant funding rate premiums during ecosystem growth phases. The token's correlation with DeFi trends and retail speculation generates predictable funding patterns for experienced arbitrageurs."},{"question":"Are there specific risks when trading SUI perpetuals on Hyperliquid?","answer":"Main risks include the DEX's newer operational history, USDC-only collateral exposure, and potential liquidity constraints during high volatility. The on-chain nature also means transaction costs during network congestion periods."},{"question":"How does Hyperliquid's on-chain settlement affect funding arbitrage strategies?","answer":"On-chain settlement provides transparency but requires gas considerations during high network activity. The sub-second finality enables rapid strategy adjustments, while the 1-hour cycles allow for more granular position management than traditional exchanges."}]}]
